I had a great time conducting the Symphonic Choir every time they joined the orchestra on stage last year, and I can't wait to work with these dedicated musicians on a weekly basis, especially given the epically brilliant choral repertoire we've got lined up this season,<\/span> <\/span>says Grant.<\/hatul><hatul >In addition, the Great Falls Symphony Association welcomes Cynthia Stevens as Assistant Choir Director. Cynthia is the Choir Director of the Great Falls College Community Choir at Great Falls College MSU, and she has performed with the Great Falls Symphonic Choir for several years. We are very pleased to have Cindy on board with us as our new Assistant Choir Director, says Executive Director, Hillary Shepherd. The professional partnership between Cindy and Grant will be dynamic, fun, and engaging for everyone involved in our choir. Cindy will be responsible for the administrative duties of the Symphonic Choir as well as lead some of the rehearsals.<span style=\"font-style:italic;\"> <\/span><\/hatul><hatul ><span style=\"\"><span style=\"font-style:italic;\">As the Assistant Choir Director, I look forward to supporting Grant and his vision for the Symphonic Choir and working with the exceptional musicians-vocal and instrumental-that we have in Great Falls.&nbsp; We are fortunate to have this caliber of talent in our community,<\/span> <\/span>says Cynthia.<\/hatul><hatul >The Great Falls Symphonic Choir is featured in three of the Great Falls Symphonys Silver Series concerts for the upcoming 2018-2019 season: <span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\"><a dataquery=\"#txtMedia207r\">Canzoni dAmore<\/a><\/span> on November 3, 2018 <span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\"><a dataquery=\"#txtMedia19ac\">Voices of Christmas<\/a><\/span> on December 2, 2018, and <span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\"><a dataquery=\"#txtMedia17sd\">Benediction<\/a><\/span> on April 13, 2019.<\/hatul><hatul >Auditions for the Great Falls Symphonic Choir will be held at&nbsp;the Mansfield Theater on Wednesday, September 5th and Thursday, September 6th from 6:00  9:30 pm. Falls Symphony Association Introduces New Principal Violist, Alyssa Roggow","date":{"_type":"wix:Date","iso":"2018-07-13T17:33:44.526Z"},"text":{"_type":"wix:RichText","text":"<hatul >The Great Falls Symphony Association is pleased to announce that Alyssa Roggow, violist, will be joining the Great Falls community as the Symphonys principal violist and the newest member of the <span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\"><a dataquery=\"#txtMedia18k8\">Cascade Quartet<\/a><\/span>.<\/hatul><hatul >Maria Ritzenthaler, who has held the position since 2015, resigned from her role to move to the Seattle-Tacoma area with her husband, composer Sam Krahn, as he was recently appointed to a teaching position at Green River College in Auburn, Washington. Viola auditions were held on Monday, June 11, and Alyssa was selected from among several candidates.<\/hatul><hatul >I'm excited to join this group of wonderful musicians and get to know the Great Falls community through our performances and outreach, says Alyssa.&nbsp;A native of Iowa, Alyssa makes&nbsp;the move from Rochester, New York, where she most recently completed graduate studies at the Eastman School of Music. Praised by the Boston Musical Intelligencer as a violist with sparkle and excellent balance, Alyssa enjoys a diverse career as a chamber musician and educator. In 2012, she toured the Midwest with the Quasari String Quartet, and has since performed in ensembles throughout New England, Canada, and Austria. In 2016, she trained in Visual Thinking Strategies, an outreach tool developed at the Museum of Modern Art in New York City, and is currently developing a series of concerts and workshops that bring chamber music and visual arts together with lively audience engagement.<\/hatul><hatul >An avid proponent of contemporary music, Alyssa regularly appears with Slee Sinfonietta at the June in Buffalo Festival, and has also performed at the New York City Electroacoustic Music Festival with Switch~Ensemble, the Red Note New Music Festival with the Quasari Quartet, and the Breaking-the- Fourth-Wall Festival Marathon with the Craig Michael Davis Ensemble. Composers she has worked with include Beat Furrer, Chaya Czernowin, Hilda Paredes, and Rand Steiger.<\/hatul><hatul >Alyssa received performance degrees from the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign and the Eastman School of Music, with further string quartet studies at Indiana University. Her primary mentor is Masumi Per Rostad. In her spare time Alyssa writes poetry, bakes, and enjoys the outdoors.<\/hatul><hatul >Alyssas joins the Great Falls Symphony Association for their 60th anniversary season. In addition to performing on the Symphonys concert series at the Mansfield Center for the Performing Arts, she will appear with the Cascade Quartet on the Chamber Music Series and in the ensembles concert and outreach tours throughout the region.<\/hatul><hatul>Cascade Quartet<\/hatul><hatul >With its depth of sound, insightful interpretations, and genre-bending performances, the Cascade Quartet has enriched communities across Montana and the Northwest for over three decades. They are praised for their cross-discipline collaborations and have worked closely with multi-media artists, dancers, choirs, world percussionists and jazz artists. Noted past collaborations include Yo-Yo Ma, the Ying Quartet, and Grammy nominee Philip Aaberg.<\/hatul><hatul >The Cascade Quartet is the resident string quartet of the Great Falls Symphony and its personnel serve as principal players in the orchestra. Each quartet member is a strong advocate for music education and outreach. They tour extensively throughout the year providing concerts, multi-day residencies and interactive school activities for communities large and small. The Cascade Quartet includes violinists Mary Papoulis and Megan Karls, violist Alyssa Roggow, and cellist Thaddeus Suits.<\/hatul><hatul>Great Falls Symphony<\/hatul><hatul >The Mission of the Great Falls Symphony is to infuse cultural vibrancy into the Great Falls community through transformative music events and education programs. The organization strives to be an essential cultural asset in North Central Montana that raises the quality of life for its citizens through outstanding performing arts programs.<\/hatul>","links":[{"linkId":"txtMedia18k8","_type":"wix:ExternalLink","target":"_blank","protocol":"http","address":"cascadequartet.org"}],"version":3},"coverImageData":{"_type":"CoverImageData","coverImageType":"photo","video":{"_type":"wix:Video","videoId":"","videoType":"","thumbnail":""},"photo":{"_type":"wix:Image","title":"","src":"c763e1_273d58ee6754459b80adf3f13817078e~mv2_d_5840_3740_s_4_2.jpg","width":5840,"height":3740},"isHD":false,"isHeroImage":false},"description":{"_type":"wix:RichText","text":"","links":[],"version":1},"mobileTitle":"Great Falls Symphony Association Introduces New Principal Violist, Alyssa Roggow","_iid":"5b48df8a6f8a3e70534f5b04","_hash":"37f0ff50ee87f2c79437efc64da7d945","_createdAt":"2018-07-13T17:21:14.127Z","_updatedAt":"2018-07-16T16:05:38.674Z","permalink":"2018\/07\/13\/Great-Falls-Symphony-Association-Introduces-New-Principal-Violist-Alyssa-Roggow","permalinkVersion":"2","defaultPost":false,"author":"","categories":[]},"5af0b3969890cc1b8fcf2175":{"_type":"MediaPost","title":"Sinfonia and Youth Orchestra Auditions","date":{"_type":"wix:Date","iso":"2018-05-07T20:19:05.981Z"},"text":{"_type":"wix:RichText","text":"<hatul style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\" >Summer break is a great time to prepare for an audition!&nbsp; Directors","_iid":"5b5212aab168b80873a5aa62","_hash":"8210aa367dbe50a9f7c4987d5e292b56","_createdAt":"2018-07-20T16:49:46.004Z","_updatedAt":"2018-07-20T17:20:58.694Z","permalink":"2018\/07\/20\/The-Great-Falls-Symphony-Association-Announces-New-Choir-Directors","permalinkVersion":"2","defaultPost":false,"author":"","categories":[],"photo":{"_type":"wix:Image","title":"","src":"c763e1_60378afd241e47cf9b5857c8066f1c37~mv2.jpg","width":546,"height":819},"httpsOnPublish":false},"5b48df8a6f8a3e70534f5b04":{"_type":"PhotoPost","title":"Great Falls Symphony Association Introduces New Principal Violist, Alyssa Roggow","date":{"_type":"wix:Date","iso":"2018-07-13T17:33:44.526Z"},"text":{"_type":"wix:RichText","text":"<hatul >The Great Falls Symphony Association is pleased to announce that Alyssa Roggow, violist, will be joining the Great Falls community as the Symphonys principal violist and the newest member of the <span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\"><a dataquery=\"#txtMedia18k8\">Cascade Quartet<\/a><\/span>.<\/hatul><hatul >Maria Ritzenthaler, who has held the position since 2015, resigned from her role to move to the Seattle-Tacoma area with her husband, composer Sam Krahn, as he was recently appointed to a teaching position at Green River College in Auburn, Washington. Viola auditions were held on Monday, June 11, and Alyssa was selected from among several candidates.<\/hatul><hatul >I'm excited to join this group of wonderful musicians and get to know the Great Falls community through our performances and outreach, says Alyssa.&nbsp;A native of Iowa, Alyssa makes&nbsp;the move from Rochester, New York, where she most recently completed graduate studies at the Eastman School of Music. Praised by the Boston Musical Intelligencer as a violist with sparkle and excellent balance, Alyssa enjoys a diverse career as a chamber musician and educator. In 2012, she toured the Midwest with the Quasari String Quartet, and has since performed in ensembles throughout New England, Canada, and Austria. In 2016, she trained in Visual Thinking Strategies, an outreach tool developed at the Museum of Modern Art in New York City, and is currently developing a series of concerts and workshops that bring chamber music and visual arts together with lively audience engagement.<\/hatul><hatul >An avid proponent of contemporary music, Alyssa regularly appears with Slee Sinfonietta at the June in Buffalo Festival, and has also performed at the New York City Electroacoustic Music Festival with Switch~Ensemble, the Red Note New Music Festival with the Quasari Quartet, and the Breaking-the- Fourth-Wall Festival Marathon with the Craig Michael Davis Ensemble. Composers she has worked with include Beat Furrer, Chaya Czernowin, Hilda Paredes, and Rand Steiger.<\/hatul><hatul >Alyssa received performance degrees from the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign and the Eastman School of Music, with further string quartet studies at Indiana University. Her primary mentor is Masumi Per Rostad. In her spare time Alyssa writes poetry, bakes, and enjoys the outdoors.<\/hatul><hatul >Alyssas joins the Great Falls Symphony Association for their 60th anniversary season. In addition to performing on the Symphonys concert series at the Mansfield Center for the Performing Arts, she will appear with the Cascade Quartet on the Chamber Music Series and in the ensembles concert and outreach tours throughout the region.<\/hatul><hatul>Cascade Quartet<\/hatul><hatul >With its depth of sound, insightful interpretations, and genre-bending performances, the Cascade Quartet has enriched communities across Montana and the Northwest for over three decades. They are praised for their cross-discipline collaborations and have worked closely with multi-media artists, dancers, choirs, world percussionists and jazz artists. Noted past collaborations include Yo-Yo Ma, the Ying Quartet, and Grammy nominee Philip Aaberg.<\/hatul><hatul >The Cascade Quartet is the resident string quartet of the Great Falls Symphony and its personnel serve as principal players in the orchestra. Each quartet member is a strong advocate for music education and outreach. They tour extensively throughout the year providing concerts, multi-day residencies and interactive school activities for communities large and small. The Cascade Quartet includes violinists Mary Papoulis and Megan Karls, violist Alyssa Roggow, and cellist Thaddeus Suits.<\/hatul><hatul>Great Falls Symphony<\/hatul><hatul >The Mission of the Great Falls Symphony is to infuse cultural vibrancy into the Great Falls community through transformative music events and education programs.
